```javascript
function switchAdjectives(sentence) {
  // Split the sentence into an array of words
  const words = sentence.split(" ");

  // Find the index of the first adjective (word that ends with 'e')
  let firstAdjIndex = -1;
  for (let I = 0; I < words.length; i++) {
    if (words[i].endsWith("e") && !words[i - 1].endsWith("e")) {
      firstAdjIndex = i;
      break;
    }
  }

  // If we couldn't find any adjectives, return the original sentence
  if (firstAdjIndex === -1) return sentence;

  // Swap the first and second adjectives (if there's a second one)
  const secondAdjIndex = firstAdjIndex - 1;
  [words[secondAdjIndex], words[firstAdjIndex]] = [words[firstAdjIndex], words[secondAdjIndex]];

  // Join the words back into a sentence
  return words.join(" ");
}
```

This function works by iterating through the words in the sentence, looking for words that end with 'e'. If it finds such a word, it assumes that it's an adjective and remembers its index. If it reaches the end of the sentence without finding any adjectives, it returns the original sentence as is.

If it does find at least one adjective, it swaps the positions of the first and second adjectives, if there's a second one. It then joins the words back into a sentence and returns the result.

